<H3> <TI>   Regenkur: Polymeric Adsorbent for Treating Purulent Lesions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Regenkur: Polymeric Adsorbent for Treating Purulent Lesions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   947C0249A Moscow KHIRURGIYA in Russian No. 11, Nov 93 
(manuscript received 29 Jun 90) pp 3-6 </F>

<F P=103> 947C0249A </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KHIRURGIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by V.K. Gostishchev, prof., L.F. Mulyayev, A.V. </F>
Nikolayev, A.G. Khanin and V.Yu. Kassin, Chairs of General 
Surgery, 2nd Therapeutic Faculty, and of Operative Surgery and 
Topographic Anatomy, 1st Therapeutic Faculty, Moscow Medical 
Institute imeni I.M. Sechenov] 
  [Abstract] Clinical trials were conducted with the 
polymeric adsorbent regenkur (previously designated tselosorb; 
weakly crosslinked cellulose ester) in the management of 
infected wounds. The patient cohort consisted of 60 men and 
women 20 to 80 years old with a variety of infected soft tissue 
wounds. Conventionally treated patients (42) with analogous 
lesions served as controls. The polymeric dressing was 
pretreated with 3% hydrogen peroxide and applied to wound 
surface in 2-3 mm thickness held in place by gauze. The number 
of changes per day varied from 3 to 14 for an average of 6.5. 
After 3 to 5 days (average 4.6 days) the experimental group 
showed significant reduction in bacterial wound contamination, 
followed by onset of granulation (4.3 days) and peripheral 
epithelialization (6.5 days). The duration of the hospital stay 
of the regenkur group was reduced by a third in comparison with 
the control patients. Thus, regenkur was shown to be an 
effective adsorbent promoting the removal of bacteria and 
exceeding the efficacy of the Swedish adsorbent debrizan [sic] 
(Pharmacia). Tables 2; references 3: 2 Russian, 1 Western. 

</TEXT>

