<F P=106> [Article by S.Yu. Safarov, M.A., prof., and M.A. Aliyev, </F>
Chair of Surgery, Stomatologic and Pediatric Faculties, Dagestan 
Medical Institute, Makhachkala] 
  [Abstract] Clinical trials were conducted with porcine 
splenic homogenates in the management of infected wounds on 30 
patients, for comparison with a control group of 30 patients 
treated in conventional manner. The outcome demonstrated the 
efficacy of 2-5 applications of the homogenate: patients in the 
experimental group were discharged from the hospital on an 
average of 13.0 +/- 0.1 days earlier than the control subjects. 
Cytologic and bacteriological workups demonstrated that in the 
experimental group pus disappeared within an average of 3.0 +/- 
0.1 days and granulation tissue appeared in 4.0 +/- 0.4 days, 
whereas in the control group analogous manifestations required 
9.0 +/- 0.4 and 8.1 +/- 0.2 days, respectively. In general, the 
effects were attributed to absorptive capacity of the 
homogenates for bacteria, their metabolites and cell detritus, 
as well as anti-inflammatory factors. Tables 1; references 3 
(Russian). 

</TEXT>

